A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds. 
(Section 12, Hindu Marriage Act, 1955)

The grounds for a voidable marriage under Section 12 HMA include: 
1. if the marriage was performed without the consent of the petitioner due to unsoundness of mind or the petitioner was suffering from mental disorder (Section 12(1)(a), HMA); 
2. if the marriage was performed without the consent of the petitioner due to being under duress (Section 12(1)(b), HMA); 
3. if the petitioner was suffering from a mental disorder or was of unsound mind at the time of marriage (Section 12(1)(b), HMA); 
4. if the respondent was suffering from a mental disorder, leprosy, or a communicable venereal disease at the time of marriage (Section 12(1)(c) and (d), HMA); 
5. if the respondent had an involuntary sexual intercourse with another person at the time of marriage (Section 12(1)(e), HMA); 
6. if the respondent was pregnant with a child of another person at the time of marriage (Section 12(1)(e), HMA); 
7. if the marriage was performed when the petitioner was below the age of 18 years for a male and 15 years for a female (Section 12(1)(f) and Prohibition of Child Marriage Act, 2006, read with Section 5(iii) of HMA).

